{"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**1.IRIS data set which non graphical EDA is performed ?**\n","\n","For the Iris dataset, several non-graphical Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) techniques can be performed to understand its structure and characteristics. The Iris dataset typically consists of 4 numerical features (sepal length, sepal width, petal length, petal width) and 1 categorical feature (species).\n","\n","Here are some common non-graphical EDA techniques and how they would apply to the Iris dataset:\n","\n","Descriptive Statistics: This involves calculating summary statistics for each numerical feature.\n","\n","Applied to Iris: For each of the four numerical features (sepal length, sepal width, petal length, petal width), you would calculate:\n","Mean: The average value.\n","Median: The middle value when sorted.\n","Mode: The most frequent value (less common for continuous data).\n","Standard Deviation: A measure of the spread of data.\n","Variance: The square of the standard deviation.\n","Min/Max: The smallest and largest values.\n","Quantiles (25th, 50th/Median, 75th percentile): These show the distribution of the data.\n","Count: Number of non-missing observations.\n","Frequency Tables and Counts: For categorical variables, this shows the number or proportion of observations in each category.\n","\n","Applied to Iris: For the 'species' variable, you would count how many instances belong to each species (e.g., setosa, versicolor, virginica). This would show if the classes are balanced or imbalanced.\n","Unique Values and Data Types: Checking the unique values in each column and their data types helps in understanding the nature of the data and identifying potential data entry errors.\n","\n","Applied to Iris: You'd confirm that 'species' has only three unique values and that the four measurements are indeed numerical (float or integer).\n","Missing Value Analysis: Identifying the presence and extent of missing values in each feature.\n","\n","Applied to Iris: You would check if any of the sepal/petal measurements or the species column have missing entries. The Iris dataset is typically clean and usually has no missing values, but in real-world scenarios, this is a crucial step.\n","Correlation Matrix: For numerical features, a correlation matrix shows the pairwise correlation coefficients, indicating the strength and direction of a linear relationship between two variables.\n","\n","Applied to Iris: You would compute the correlation between all pairs of numerical features (e.g., sepal length vs. petal length, sepal width vs. petal width). This helps in understanding how these physical characteristics relate to each other.\n","Grouped Descriptive Statistics: Calculating descriptive statistics for numerical features, grouped by a categorical feature.\n","\n","Applied to Iris: You could calculate the mean, median, standard deviation, etc., of sepal length, sepal width, petal length, and petal width for each species (setosa, versicolor, virginica). This is very insightful for the Iris dataset as it highlights the differences in measurements between the species.\n","These non-graphical methods\n","\n","**2.In  Air Quality data set which graph is used to perform multivariate analysis?**\n","\n","\n","For multivariate analysis in an Air Quality dataset, which typically involves multiple pollutants, meteorological factors, and possibly temporal/spatial dimensions, several types of graphs can be very effective:\n","\n","Scatter Plot Matrix (Pair Plot): This is excellent for visualizing the pairwise relationships between multiple numerical variables. Each cell in the matrix displays a scatter plot of one variable against another, and often histograms or density plots on the diagonals. For air quality, it can help identify correlations between different pollutants (e.g., PM2.5 vs. NO2) or between pollutants and meteorological factors (e.g., PM2.5 vs. temperature, wind speed).\n","\n","Heatmaps (especially of Correlation Matrices): A heatmap can visualize the correlation coefficients between all pairs of numerical variables in your dataset. This provides a quick overview of which variables are strongly positively, negatively, or not correlated at all. For air quality, it can concisely show relationships between various pollutants and weather conditions.\n","\n","Parallel Coordinates Plot: This graph is particularly useful for visualizing high-dimensional data. Each variable has its own vertical axis, and each observation is represented as a line that connects points on these axes. It's great for identifying clusters, trends, and patterns across many variables simultaneously. For air quality, you could plot levels of different pollutants, temperature, and humidity, and visually track specific days or events.\n","\n","Principal Component Analysis (PCA) Plots / Biplots: While PCA is a dimensionality reduction technique, its results are often visualized. A PCA plot (or biplot) can show the relationships between observations and the original variables in a reduced 2D or 3D space. It helps to identify underlying patterns, groups of similar observations, and which original variables contribute most to the variance. This is valuable for understanding complex air quality interactions.\n","\n","Multi-line Time Series Plots: If your air quality data has a temporal component (which it almost always does), plotting multiple pollutants (e.g., PM2.5, O3, NO2) and possibly meteorological variables (e.g., temperature) on the same time axis allows for direct visual comparison of their trends, seasonality, and co-variation over time.\n","\n","Grouped Box Plots or Violin Plots: If you want to see how the distribution of a pollutant (numerical) varies across different categories defined by two other factors (e.g., PM2.5 by season and by location type), grouped box plots can be very informative.\n","\n","The choice of graph depends on the specific aspect of multivariate relationships you want to explore or highlight.\n","\n","**3.In Wine quality data set can you do non graphical EDA ? Explain your answer.**\n","\n","Descriptive Statistics: This is fundamental. For every numerical column, you would calculate:\n","\n","Mean, Median, Mode: To understand the central tendency of each chemical property and the 'quality' score.\n","Standard Deviation, Variance: To measure the spread or variability of the properties.\n","Min, Max, Quartiles (25th, 50th/Median, 75th percentile): To understand the range and distribution of values, identifying potential outliers or skewness.\n","Count: To check for the number of non-missing observations for each feature.\n","Explanation: This would quickly reveal the typical range of, say, alcohol content, the average pH, or the distribution of quality ratings, and help detect any immediate anomalies.\n","Frequency Tables and Counts: Especially useful for discrete numerical variables like the 'quality' score (if treated as an ordinal categorical variable) or any truly categorical features (e.g., 'wine type' if the dataset combines red and white wines).\n","\n","Explanation: A frequency table for 'quality' would show how many wines received a rating of 3, 4, 5, etc., indicating if the quality distribution is balanced or skewed towards certain ratings.\n","Unique Values and Data Types: Examining the data types of each column (e.g., float for chemical properties, integer for quality) and checking for unique values in discrete columns.\n","\n","Explanation: This helps confirm data integrity. For instance, ensuring pH values are floats and quality scores are integers within an expected range (e.g., 0-10). It can also catch data entry errors if unexpected unique values appear.\n","Missing Value Analysis: Identifying and quantifying missing values across all columns.\n","\n","Explanation: Knowing which columns have missing data and how much is crucial for deciding on imputation strategies or if certain features need to be dropped. For example, if 'sulphates' has 30% missing values, that's important to know early.\n","Correlation Matrix: Computing the pairwise correlation coefficients between all numerical features.\n","\n","Explanation: This matrix would show how different chemical properties relate to each other (e.g., is fixed acidity highly correlated with citric acid?) and, most importantly, how each chemical property correlates with 'quality'. This can give initial insights into which properties might be driving wine quality.\n","Grouped Descriptive Statistics: If there's a categorical variable (e.g., 'wine type' - red/white) or even groups derived from 'quality' (e.g., 'low quality' vs. 'high quality'), you can calculate descriptive statistics for numerical features within each group.\n","\n","Explanation: For example, comparing the mean alcohol content, pH, or volatile acidity for 'red wine' versus 'white wine' could highlight significant differences between the two types, or comparing chemical properties for wines rated 'good' versus 'bad'.\n","By performing these non-graphical EDA techniques, you gain a robust understanding of the Wine Quality dataset's structure, the distribution of its variables, potential data issues, and initial relationships between features, all without needing to generate a single plot.\n","\n"],"metadata":{"id":"tWvG_9sJY4Te"}}],"metadata":{"colab":{"toc_visible":true,"provenance":[{"file_id":"/v2/external/notebooks/intro.ipynb","timestamp":1775757566955}]},"kernelspec":{"display_name":"Python 3","name":"python3"}},"nbformat":4,"nbformat_minor":0}